##Chatting and drawing comic books, these doctors and nurses know "18 kinds of martial arts"

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter, Wang Xuanhui, intern, Liu Yudan, thepaper.cn

"I'm in the hospital. What about my cat? "

"Every day I take this medicine, is it going to work? "

Fujian Aid Hubei nurses draw cartoons to encourage patients. CREDIT: Interviewee, video editor: Wu Chia-Ying 01:06

After arriving in Wuhan, Hubei Province, Chen Hsiao-Huan began to feel the patients'anxiety, and she began to think: in the face of anxiety, what can the nursing staff do?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the Intensive Care Unit, nurses take care of patients'daily life, medication and other nursing work. Photo: Courtesy of the respondents

Chen Hsiao-Huan, director of the Nursing Department at the Fujian Provincial Hospital, arrived in Wuhan on Feb. 13 with the Fujian Aid Hubei Medical Team, and is currently at the Wuhan Union Hospital, to be responsible for the nursing management of the new severe coronary pneumonia ward in Z12 ward.

Some might argue that the most important part of a patient's recovery is therapy. In Chen Hsiao-Huan's view, however, keeping a patient in good spirits is as critical as treatment.

"A person's immune system is weakened when he or she is depressed, which can affect rest, sleep and diet. If the patient is in a good mood, the immune system will naturally improve,"Chen Hsiao-Huan told the www.thepaper.cn  , to be sure, a good mood can help a patient recover quickly.

In addition to taking care of the patients'daily lives, daily activities and medication, Chen Hsiao-Huan led the nursing team to set up a psychological counseling group to provide psychological counseling to anxiety patients through such measures as talk therapy and supportive psychotherapy, open the patient's heart, listen to their talk, ease their worry, anxiety, tension and other negative emotions.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Little anxiety and big concern

In the Z12 Ward, the inpatients were all the severe cases of new coronary pneumonia, the proportion of patients over 60 years old was more than 60% .

When each patient was admitted, the nurses used the self-rating depression and anxiety inventory for inpatients to assess their psychology. "There are people who look normal and don't know what's wrong until they've been evaluated, and nurses who have a score of more than six give them psychological intervention, " Chen Hsiao-Huan said.

At the same time, they also found that some patients in the assessment is normal, but sometimes prone to mood fluctuations and fluctuations, also need the care and attention of nurses.

Psychological anxiety and anxiety is mainly reflected in the language of the excessive. "He's impatient, he doesn't talk to you, he doesn't talk to you, sometimes he doesn't cooperate, " said Chen Hsiao-Huan, who had a patient who wondered if his daily medication was working? Is there a problem? Is it poison? In a constant state of anxiety, distrust, and uncooperation.

For some anxious patients, Chen Hsiao-Huan led the nurses through word therapy, engaging them in skilled conversation, distracting them from the illness and getting them to speak their minds. In fact, she found that many patients affect the mood is a little anxiety, in the outside world, may be small things.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The nurses in the Nursing Group 7 of Fujian Provincial Hospital used their rest time to draw various "cheering pictures" for the patients.

For example, there is a patient, the family has a puppy, the patient first went to the shelter hospital, and then was transferred to Z12 Ward treatment. His dog had been left unattended for a few days, and he was so anxious that he thought to himself, what about my dog? Patients call the community many times to contact the community, the community staff heavy task, also can not take care of. At this time, he is more agitated, and the nurse exchanges, also can say some of the more aggressive language.

All of this, the responsible nurse in the eyes, anxious in the heart. Since they could not use mobile phones in the isolation area of the hospital, they used their mobile phones to help contact the community when they came out after work. They called several times that night. There was no answer there either.

The next day, at the insistence of the nurse's Veronica Guerin, he finally contacted the community and begged the community staff to go to the patient's home and shoot a video of the dog being taken and sent to the patient. "He was very happy and kept thanking the nurse, " he said

Another diabetic, who uses a 6 mm Needle for daily insulin injections, had an 8 mm needle in his ward, very unhappy: "How to return a responsibility, why to give me with 8 mm needle, don't you know? Very painful. "

"When a patient is angry, it's important not to add fuel to the fire, " Chen Hsiao-Huan says. Finally, after work, Chen Hsiao-Huan went to the pharmacy outside the hospital and bought a 6 mm needle. Once inside, the patient is happy and feels things have been resolved. "It's simple, but it's about the details, and it's about the small things that make the patient feel loved and cared for, " Chen Hsiao-Huan said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"We have come a long way to take care of you, " Chen Hsiao-Huan's care team wrote in a letter to patients with new crown pneumonia

Inspire the residents with letters and cartoons

Living in isolation wards, where patients are cut off from their families, cut off from the outside world, many people don't know what they're facing with a disease like this? Online clutter and negative emotions can also cause anxiety.

To this end, Chen Hsiao-Huan's care team wrote a letter to the patient, telling the patient, "We understand how you feel. We came all the way to Wuhan to take care of you. " The letter gave many patients confidence and courage.

She remembers a family of three coming into the hospital at the same time, and starting to treat the nurses with a nonchalant attitude and a reluctance to talk. After that, doctors talk to their children, not about their illness, but about school. Parents see the child chat is very happy, the initiative to come over. Slowly, a family of three doctors, nurses have developed a good feeling, the chatterbox is also open, and now is gradually returning to health.

One patient was angry at first because the meal was late. The nurse stayed with her and listened to her. Finally, the patient felt embarrassed. "In fact, I felt better after I said it. ". When she left, the nurse assured her that her needs would be taken care of during dinner.

Another patient is a doctor, unfortunately infected with the disease was admitted to the Z12 Ward, has been discharged. Before leaving the hospital, he thanked the nurses: "Your doctors and nurses care about every patient, often accompanied by talking, the first day in the hospital, I told my case, obviously feel much better. "

In the seventh group, led by Chen Hsiao-Huan, nurses drew cartoons by hand overnight to encourage patients and boost their confidence. They drew scenes of life and work in the ward in the form of "big white, " such as a cart handing out lunch, in a Hazmat suit. There are also a lot of words of encouragement beside the cartoon, such as "you are the best" , "eat enough, only have the strength to defeat the virus" and so on. When the nurses handed out the comics to the patients, Chen Hsiao-Huan said, they saw happy faces and heard words of thanks.

In the Z12 Ward, Chen Hsiao-Huan's nursing team has received more than a dozen thank-you notes from discharged patients. She and the nurses have also set up a "wall of good wishes" , posting messages and thank-you notes, hope to take this to encourage patients who are still in hospital: "Let us face up to each other, watch each other, to meet the day of discharge. "

This issue is edited by Chang Chen
